***************************************************************************
                    Equipment Power and Gearcheck
***************************************************************************

Weapons, armour, implants, and other objects inheriting EQUIP expose a common
power-scoring API. The player command "gearcheck" uses this API to compare
carried equipment against the equipment and slots a player is currently using.

***************************************************************************
                             Item Level
***************************************************************************

Every object inheriting EQUIP can declare its intended progression level:

====================
set_item_level(150);
====================

|CKBvoid set_item_level(int level);|XX0
        Sets the equipment's item level. Values are bounded from 0 through
        the current player level cap of 250. Level 0 means that legacy or
        deliberately unranked equipment has no item level. Calling this
        function, including with 0, is an explicit override of area inference.

|CKBvoid clear_item_level();|XX0
        Removes an explicit override and allows the equipment to infer its
        level again from the owning area's catalog metadata.

|CKBint query_item_level();|XX0
        Returns the explicit item level when one was set. Otherwise, the first
        query resolves the equipment blueprint's owning area and caches that
        area's equipment level on the object. This API is shared by weapons,
        armour, implants, cyberware, relics, and other EQUIP descendants.

Item level describes the progression context for which an item was designed.
It is not a minimum-use restriction: use set_level_restriction() separately
when a real mechanical gate is required. For implants, cyberware, relics, and
other non-weapon/non-armour equipment, item level remains descriptive unless
the owning mechanic explicitly consumes it.

Weapons and armour use item level in physical combat. Their inherent rating is:

====================
min(25, item_level / 10)
====================

A weapon uses the rating as inherent armour penetration. Armour uses it as
inherent armour strength. The ratings oppose each other, so equal-level gear
preserves the ordinary combat result:

====================
armour factor = 100 + armour strength - weapon penetration
armour factor is bounded from 75 through 125
====================

Level 150 therefore supplies a 15% rating and level 250 supplies 25%. Worn
armour strength is weighted by each piece's absorb contribution; a small ring
cannot raise an otherwise weak suit to its own item level. Only worn armour's
share of physical flat reduction, percentage reduction, and armour-derived
absorb chance participates. Intrinsic absorb, temporary absorption, shields,
resistances, guild mitigation, boss reduction, dodge, accuracy, and
nonphysical damage are unchanged.

NPCs without a weapon use their capped monster level as the item level of
natural physical attacks. NPC intrinsic armour likewise uses capped monster
level when worn armour is not supplying the effective absorb class. When worn
armour overtakes the NPC's intrinsic armour floor, the actual worn equipment
levels are used instead. These fallbacks do not apply to unarmed or naked
players, and boss tier remains separate from item level.

The matchup applies after the ordinary physical-armour cap is calculated.
DAM_AP then halves the remaining armour contribution. Do not manually add a
power feature for inherent penetration or strength; EQUIPMENT_POWER_D scores
both automatically.

Area-owned equipment normally needs no setter. Its blueprint path resolves
through AREA_CATALOG_D, which uses area.json's optional equipment_level or the
midpoint of recommended_min_level and recommended_max_level. The result is
cached, so combat does not repeatedly query the catalog. Existing objects keep
their resolved value; newly cloned objects see refreshed catalog metadata.

Use set_item_level() for boss, quest, shop, crafted, generated, shared-path, or
otherwise exceptional rewards whose intended progression differs from the
surrounding area. Shared-path equipment cannot infer where it was acquired.
Use set_item_level(0) to deliberately opt an item out of area inference.

Normal structured properties are scored automatically, including weapon class,
hit bonus, armour dodge and absorb class, equipment stats, resistances, sigils,
item-level armour penetration and strength, standard weapon and armour
modifications, generated item procs, implant procs, cyberware strain,
durability, and temporary item warnings.

Custom scripted callbacks cannot be executed while an item is being inspected.
Running weapon_hit(), wear_func(), or an implant callback during gearcheck could
damage something, change state, or otherwise cause side effects. Builders must
therefore describe the relative value of custom effects explicitly.

***************************************************************************
                         Declaring Custom Effects
***************************************************************************

|CKBvoid add_power_feature(string sId, int iPower, string sDescription,
    string sCategory);|XX0

Adds or replaces one explicitly scored feature on the equipment.

    sId
        A stable lowercase identifier. Use underscores instead of spaces.
        Reusing an identifier replaces the previous declaration.

    iPower
        The feature's relative power contribution. Positive values make the
        item stronger; negative values represent a drawback or tradeoff.

    sDescription
        Short text describing the mechanical effect being scored.

    sCategory
        One of "offense", "defense", "utility", or "reliability".
        Invalid or omitted categories default to "utility".

Example:

====================
add_power_feature("scripted_hit", 300,
  "Burning cinder on-hit burst", "offense");
====================

Power values should reflect the effect's expected value over ordinary play,
not its maximum possible single activation. Consider damage or healing amount,
activation chance, cooldown, duration, targeting limits, reliability, and any
cost paid by the player. Compare the result with similar existing items and
inspect it with "gearcheck <item>" before release.

Do not add declarations for properties already scored automatically. For
example, do not manually score weapon class, AC, add_equipment_stat(),
resistances, sigils, standard modifications, or structured generated procs.
Doing so would count the same power twice.

***************************************************************************
                    Required Scripted Feature IDs
***************************************************************************

Use these exact identifiers for the standard opaque equipment hooks:

    "scripted_hit"
        A weapon using set_hit_func() or set_hit_obj().

    "scripted_wield"
        A weapon using set_wield_func() or set_wield_obj() when the callback
        grants a benefit or drawback beyond permission checks and messaging.

    "scripted_wear"
        Armour using set_wear_func() or set_wear_obj() when the callback
        grants a benefit or drawback beyond permission checks and messaging.

For an implant proc whose effect is "call_function", use the proc's exact
"id" as the power feature identifier.

Example implant callback:

====================
add_power_feature("offhand_cleave", 540,
  "Armour-piercing off-hand cleave", "offense");
add_implant_proc(([
  "id" : "offhand_cleave",
  "trigger" : "combat_hit",
  "chance" : 17,
  "cooldown" : 6,
  "effect" : "call_function",
  "function" : "execute_offhand_cleave"
]));
====================

If the required declaration is missing, gearcheck marks the item UNCERTAIN.
Its visible score still includes all measurable properties, but the scripted
effect is omitted from that score.

***************************************************************************
                         Supporting Functions
***************************************************************************

|CKBvoid remove_power_feature(string sId);|XX0
        Removes one explicit feature declaration.

|CKBmapping query_power_features();|XX0
        Returns a copy of all explicit feature declarations. Each entry
        contains "power", "description", and "category".

|CKBint query_power(object oPlayer);|XX0
        Returns the item's final integer power score. Pass the player when
        player-specific context is available.

|CKBmapping query_power_profile(object oPlayer);|XX0
        Returns the full scoring explanation used by gearcheck. Important
        fields include:

            "score"           final non-negative score
            "item_level"      declared progression level, or 0 when unranked
            "offense"         offensive subtotal
            "defense"         defensive subtotal
            "utility"         stats, resources, and general utility
            "reliability"     durability and reliability adjustments
            "components"      individual scored reasons
            "warnings"        restrictions and temporary-item notes
            "unknown_effects" scripted effects not yet declared
            "confidence"      "high", "uncertain", or "invalid"

|CKBvoid set_power_adjustment(int iPower);|XX0
        Adds a general item-specific correction to the final score.
        Prefer add_power_feature() for named mechanics because it provides
        a useful explanation. Use this only when a named feature cannot
        reasonably describe the correction.

|CKBint query_power_adjustment(object oPlayer);|XX0
        Returns the general correction. An unusual item may override this
        function when its correction genuinely depends on the player.
        It must be deterministic and must not change game state.

***************************************************************************
                              Guidelines
***************************************************************************

* Power scoring is comparison guidance, not permission to exceed equipment
  balance, uniqueness, guild, or area-building rules.
* Annotation functions must be called during normal item configuration, such
  as reset() or a tier/grade configuration function.
* Scoring functions and overrides must never deal damage, send combat spam,
  consume resources, roll random outcomes, or modify the player or item.
* Keep identifiers stable so saved or restored equipment remains explainable.
* When an effect changes by tier or grade, calculate its declared power from
  that same tier or grade.
* Validate the result in game with "gearcheck <item>" and compare it with
  equipment intended for the same level and slot.
